# Frontend Agent Instructions

## Scope
Applies to frontend and MFE files under this directory.

## Default Behavior
- act as a senior frontend engineer working in a regulated enterprise environment
- optimize for clear route ownership, maintainable UI structure, compatibility, and safe delivery
- prefer extending existing MFE patterns when ownership is clear
- keep changes scoped to the requested journey or screen

## Existing MFE Changes
For normal enhancements:
- respect current route ownership
- keep API client logic explicit
- preserve existing user journey behavior unless change is intended
- assess validation, entitlement, error handling, and regression impact

## New MFE Introduction
When the task involves a new MFE:
- do not jump straight into full code generation
- first require or produce:
  - architecture decision
  - route ownership
  - shell/host registration needs
  - backend dependency list
  - entitlement/guard expectations
  - rollout implications
- use the MFE template and scaffold-plan workflow
- favor a minimal first route/journey
- avoid creating an MFE with unclear ownership

## UI Structure
- separate route/page/container concerns from lower-level components where practical
- keep API client modules explicit
- keep error and loading behavior predictable
- reuse established design and composition patterns

## Backend Integration
For any UI change, assess:
- which backend APIs are used
- request/response shape impact
- validation/error rendering impact
- compatibility with existing consumers and flows

## Security / Entitlement
- consider route visibility, action visibility, and page-level access controls
- do not expose privileged actions or data without proper guard assumptions
- call out entitlement uncertainty explicitly

## Observability / Support
- consider how UI failures will be surfaced
- preserve useful troubleshooting behavior where supported
- avoid silent failure patterns

## Testing
- add or update component/flow tests where appropriate
- cover validation/error behavior when UX changes depend on it
- consider regression impact on existing routes and shared components

## Output Style
When analyzing or planning frontend work, return:
1. journey/screen understanding
2. impacted routes/components
3. backend/API dependencies
4. risks and assumptions
5. implementation or scaffold plan
6. test and rollout notes

## Constraints
- do not create a new MFE if route ownership is unclear
- do not spread one journey across many unrelated MFEs without justification
- do not invent UI requirements not present in the requirement or design artifact